	(7471,795,'page_description','After building three successful energy companies in 12 years, the only thing left to do was to start a fourth. FourPoint Energy is an exploration and production company founded by the leadership team of Cordillera Energy Partners. With over 30 years of industry leadership, FourPoint has a history to support its future growth to seek its greatest untapped resource: Opportunity.'),
	(7472,795,'_page_description','field_56f0d08ab57b3'),
	(7473,795,'timeline_items_0_timeline_year','2000'),
	(7474,795,'_timeline_items_0_timeline_year','field_56fab9c610702'),
	(7475,795,'timeline_items_0_timeline_description','Cordillera Energy Partners was founded in February 2000 and incorporated as a Limited Liability Company formed in the state of Texas. The Company formed by George Solich, President and CEO, and his management team, employed the “acquire/exploit” strategy—buying producing assets and underdeveloped assets in three core areas. They enhanced production, cash flow, and reserves through a combination of drilling and lowering the cost structure, while adding additional “bolt-on” acquisitions.'),
	(7476,795,'_timeline_items_0_timeline_description','field_56fab9e210703'),
	(7477,795,'timeline_items_0_timeline_image','780'),
	(7478,795,'_timeline_items_0_timeline_image','field_56fabab98eafe'),
	(7479,795,'timeline_items_1_timeline_year','2003'),
	(7480,795,'_timeline_items_1_timeline_year','field_56fab9c610702'),
	(7481,795,'timeline_items_1_timeline_description','The core areas for Cordillera Energy Partners I (CEP I) were the Anadarko Basin, the Delaware Basin and the San Juan Basin. Through a combination of acquisitions and drilling, CEP I grew its production to 30 MMCFED, annual cash flow to $35 million, and proved reserves to 250 BCFE by mid-2003. In October 2003, CEP I sold its assets to Patina Oil & Gas for cash and warrants to purchase Patina stock valued at $247 million.'),
	(7482,795,'_timeline_items_1_timeline_description','field_56fab9e210703'),
	(7483,795,'timeline_items_1_timeline_image','781'),
	(7484,795,'_timeline_items_1_timeline_image','field_56fabab98eafe'),
	(7485,795,'timeline_items_2_timeline_year','2004'),
	(7486,795,'_timeline_items_2_timeline_year','field_56fab9c610702'),
	(7487,795,'timeline_items_2_timeline_description','Upon completion of the CEP I sale, the core management team formed CEP II, again with EnCap Investments, seven along-side institutional investors and management. In March of 2004, the company was capitalized with a $200 million private equity investment and a $300 million credit facility from six banks led by JP Morgan Chase. CEP II added to its management team ranks and set out to chart the same “acquire/exploit” strategy that had been so successful in CEP I.'),
	(7488,795,'_timeline_items_2_timeline_description','field_56fab9e210703'),
	(7489,795,'timeline_items_2_timeline_image','782'),
	(7490,795,'_timeline_items_2_timeline_image','field_56fabab98eafe'),
	(7491,795,'timeline_items_3_timeline_year','2007'),
	(7492,795,'_timeline_items_3_timeline_year','field_56fab9c610702'),
	(7493,795,'timeline_items_3_timeline_description','Prior to the sale of CEP II, the management team and CEP’s equity investors elected to form CEP III, LLC, while still managing and operating CEP II so as not to lose momentum, opportunities, or talent. In March of 2007, CEP III was formed with a $500 million equity investment from EnCap Investments, along-side institutional investors and management. CEP III also entered into a $600 million, six bank credit facility again led by JP Morgan Chase.'),
	(7494,795,'_timeline_items_3_timeline_description','field_56fab9e210703'),
	(7495,795,'timeline_items_3_timeline_image','783'),
	(7496,795,'_timeline_items_3_timeline_image','field_56fabab98eafe'),
	(7497,795,'timeline_items_4_timeline_year','2008'),
	(7498,795,'_timeline_items_4_timeline_year','field_56fab9c610702'),
	(7499,795,'timeline_items_4_timeline_description','Through a combination of focused acquisitions and vertical and horizontal drilling, CEP II grew quickly in both size and value. By mid-2008 CEP II was producing close to 50 MMCFED from 600 wells (97% operated with annual cash flow exceeding $200 million and proved reserves of 725 BCFE.) These high-quality natural gas assets were concentrated in the Texas Panhandle (Douglas, Cleveland, Granite Wash, Atoka, and Morrow), West Central Anadarko Basin, and the East Texas Basin (Cotton Valley Sand, Cotton Valley Lime, Houston, Pettet, and Travis Peak).  \r\n\r\n\r\nIn September of 2008 CEP II sold all the assets of the company in three separate transactions for total consideration in cash and stock valued at $1.023 billion. The Texas Panhandle and East Texas assets were sold to Forest Oil, the Oklahoma assets to Merit Energy, and the Deep Woodford assets to Devon Energy.'),
